"Mais qu'est ce qu'un PVT..? ", "Oh, tu pars en vacances ?!", "Mais comment fais-tu pour financer ton voyage...?!" ✈️

Autant de questions que l'on m'a fréquemment posées et qui reflètent bien le fait que ce programme n'est pas assez mis en avant par nos gouvernements et systèmes éducatifs !!! 🚦🛑

Le PVT (Programme Vacances Travail) est un accord entre deux pays permettant l'obtention d'un Visa de travail et de loisirs, en règle générale d'une durée de un an. Cela peut être moins, comme plus selon le pays en question 🇵🇪 / 🇫🇷

Il permet de choisir, d'alterner entre le travail, le volontariat🤝 (tel que le woofing, HelpX, Workaway...), et les visites d'un pays en ayant également la possibilité de se déplacer dans les pays aux alentours 🗺

Le PVT requiert malheureusement une limite d'âge 👼 et des économies 💰💶 afin de pouvoir subsister sur place sur les temps de loisirs...

C'est une belle expérience qui signifie immersion dans d'autres cultures🤠, d'autres traditions👩‍🌾, apprendre ou réapprendre une langue étrangère, des dialectes, partir à la rencontre de l'inconnu🗽 tout en ayant la sécurité d'obtenir un revenu si besoin 🪂

Il est fort dommage que celui-ci soit limité aux personnes de moins de 35/30 ans... Cela est mon avis personnel, car il n'y a pas d'âge pour découvrir le monde 🌍 Toutefois, le voyage est accessible à tous.tes par le biais du volontariat🤝, et chaque pays dispose plus ou moins d'une durée de Visa légale de 90 jours, ce qui peut être une belle expérience pour toute personne désirant vivre de nouvelles aventures ! ✨️🪅🎲

Croyons en nos rêves, et osons sortir de nos sentiers battus !

🌎🏞🏜🇵🇪

BLACK DIAMOND Distance 8L. |

Esta Distance 8, es realmente singular. La posicionaría a medio camino entre una mochila de aproximación y una de trail, y eso se nota en la resistencia de los materiales empleados, especialmente en la parte trasera de carga, si la comparamos con los modelos más populares.

¿Cómo se distribuye?

Parte trasera:
Zona de carga totalmente diáfana y 2 espacios laterales (casi ocultos para los bastones).
Tiene un pequeño bolsillo con cremallera interior, para teléfono, documentación etc. Me gusta.
Para llevar el sistema trasero de hidratación dispone de un espacio dedicado al que se accede por la única abertura.
El compartimento se abre y se cierra mediante un cordino tensor, y la solapa ‘enrollable’.
En los laterales, unos tensores para comprimir la carga.
El material es impermeable y resistente en extremo.

Parte delantera y lateral:
Tipo chaleco y bastante común, con espacio para bidones (no incluidos) y bolsillos superpuestos (izquierdo con cremallera).
En los laterales, también hay bolsillo de malla elástica con solapa.

Tiene un sistema portabastones, algo peculiar, y en mi opinión poco práctico. Tanto, que no lo uso.
La solución es introducir los bastones en el lateral (posición vertical) entre el tejido externo e interno (ojo aquí con las rosetas de los bastones para no romper nada).
Por lo demás, una mochila comodísima, capaz y resistente en zonas con vegetación cerrada. Totalmente a prueba de enganchones.
Los acabados son muy buenos, y la posición de los bidones, sumado al ajuste, hace que el rebote al correr sea inexistente.
Muy indicada para carreras que demandan cierta cantidad de material, y climatología adversa.
Si los 8 litros se te quedan cortos, existe una versión de 15 litros, por 175$.

¿Qué te parece esta mochila?
👇📝👀

March 17 - 20, 2021

(Post 2 of 2)

On St. Patrick's Day, Robert, the manager of the Palace Hotel, gave us a ride back to the trailhead in the Pinos Altos, where Freebird had left off at the other day. We weren't walking far today, and were hoping to at least make it to Our Lady of Guadalupe Monastery for Vespers that evening. I don't recall the mileage there from the trailhead, but I think it was more or less 5 miles. We walked leisurely all afternoon, stopping to talk with a trail maintainer for a few hours. At that point we thought we were actually going to be late, but we found the side trail to the monastery and made it just in time. Brother Lawrence radiantly greeted us at the gift shop. He left and returned with bottled water, two Ziploc bags of apples and oranges, a box of electrolyte mixes, a bag of their Irish blend coffee (the monks there roast and sell coffee), and two Benedictine medals with an accompanying booklet about the saint. Lawrence gave us directions on how to locate our friend Doug the Hermit (See previous post: https://www.instagram.com/p/CuRyDkbLZxC/?utm_source=ig_web_copy_link&igsh=MzRlODBiNWFlZA==), whose place was off of our maps this year. We stayed for Vespers and then dropped back down the side trail, finding a place to camp on a ridge.

The next day the CDT circled around the monastery. We couldn't find the turnoff that led to Doug's place, so we continued on our route into the eastern end of the Pinos Altos. We crossed Highway 15, just north of Pinos Altos town, and camped in a ponderosa forest. On the 19th, a couple day-hikers from Silver City joined us for lunch. We gave them the coffee from Brother Lawrence, as we had no way of brewing it, nor did we want to carry that much.

(Story continued in comments)

Just five hours north of San Francisco sits a gem of the backpacking world, The Lost Coast. Never in my wildest dreams did I imagine I would find such a remote and spectacular coastal destination in the most populous state in the US.

For five days we experienced mile after mile of pristine black sand beaches, old growth redwoods, herds of elk, barking sea lions, and the sound of ocean waves soothing us to sleep. We had the sense that we travelled to the far reaches of the earth, but strangely, no one stamped our passports. Repost: @rachid.dahnoun

Gym Review #3 

SciFitness 

A gym as uninspiring as the city itself. I haven’t been to many places that I’d absolutely never return to but Cebu is definitely one of them and this gym unfortunately followed in its city’s footstep. 

The gym itself is located on the third floor of a run down building on a busy street. On first impressions the actual gym looked like a good place to workout and at 100 pesos was very cheap, however, SciFitness’s biggest problem is that it is like working out in a Sauna with the demotivating music of Taylor Swift in the background. The heat and the music choice combined both contributed to a negative workout atmosphere. Don’t get me wrong the Philippines is a hot place but the lack of air con or open windows made working out for longer than 10 minutes and not ending up in a sweaty dripping mess nearly impossible. 

There are some positives to the gym though if you can bare the heat. 
1. The price is cheap.
2. There is a fair amount of equipment available and everything worked.
3. The staff are friendly and helpful. 

On the whole SciFitness has negative and positives if you want a cheap workout, can handle the heat and Taylor swift is your choice of workout music then SciFitness is for you. 

⭐️⭐️⭐️

It’s almost 8 years since we quit the 9-5  life to travel the world, so I thought I’d share 8 important things I’ve learned along the way ❤️

1. Planning helps you discover hidden gems, but booking makes you rigid. Allow for spontaneity and flexibility with your plans and don’t book everything in advance. 

2. The connections you make on the road are deeper than you can imagine, and the people you meet understand you on a level that others can’t understand 🫶🏻 if you’re feeling like you’ve not met your tribe yet, solo travel! 

3. You need a lot less than you think you do. All the clutter and *stuff* that comes with a ‘settled’ life loses meaning, and you realise you need very little to be happy 😊

4. Travelling together makes your relationship more solid. We had to adjust to travelling together, and now we have such a great flow with travel that I hate doing it without him! 

5.  You have to go with an open mind to get the true benefits of travel. Try as many new experiences as you can, talk to everyone, eat everything, and don’t be afraid to look stupid or ask questions. It’s part of the process! 

6. Be able to say yes, no, hello, please, and thank you in the local language. It invites conversation and shows a willingness to learn about the culture! Think of how much you’ll learn over the years ❤️ 

7. You’ll only be nervous for a little bit, then your confidence will grow and you’ll be unstoppable! 

8. It’s not as hard or expensive as you think. Your mind just like to worry too much! 

Travel will grow your mind, change your outlook / goals / ambitions, and introduce you to the best people ❤️ Long term travellers, is there anything you would add?
